This is ACRIS -- Advanced, Controllable Room Illumination System

Born out of a project I worked on over January and February of 2011, ACRIS is a
system designed to provide precise control of high-powered LEDs.  It consists
of a set of LED controller boards, which drive LEDs using constant-current sink
drivers and are controlled over an RS-485 network, and a communications board,
which interfaces with a computer over USB and talks to the LED controllers.
This hardware is very easily controlled via simple serial commands sent by
software.

My goal for ACRIS is to provide a complete stack from base hardware to
software.

Features:
    - Each LED controller supports up to 15 channels, with each channel sinking
      up to 360mA
    - Each channel has 4096 levels of brightness
    - LED controllers are around 2.3"x3.9"
    - Status LEDs on the board tell you what the hell is going on
    - LED controllers have a bootloader, so you can program a new main
      application, set the addresses of various controllers, and set
      the application baud rate all over the RS-485 network!
    - You can even control which devices you program; you can act on single
      devices, blocks of devices, or all devices at once!

This repository has a lot of stuff that's continually being updated.
